\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared to cognitive functions such as language, the visual detection of
 motion may seem trivial, yet the underlying neural mechanisms have remained
 elusive for half a century 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Borst:2011vn,Vaney:2012cr"

\end_inset

.
 Some retinal outputs (ganglion cells) respond selectively to visual stimuli
 moving in particular directions, while retinal inputs (photoreceptors)
 lack direction selectivity (DS).
 How does DS emerge from the microcircuitry connecting inputs to outputs?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DS has been observed in the starburst amacrine cell (SAC), and several types
 of directionally selective ganglion cells (DSGCs).
 It has been shown that the upstream source of excitation to these cells,
 which is provided by retinal bipolar cells (BCs) lacks DS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yonehara:2013hc"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, the mechanism of DS arises somewhere in the region of the retina
 where these cells interact, the inner plexiform layer (IPL).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Retinal bipolar cells
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bipolar cells (BCs) provide the sole pathway from the photoreceptors of
 the retina to the amacrine and ganglion cells of the IPL.
 Since most amacrine cells (ACs) are inhibitory, and ganglion cells (GCs)
 do not synapse presynaptically within the IPL, BCs can be considered the
 primary source of excitatory input to the IPL.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Retinal bipolar cells were first subdivided into classes by the polarity
 of their central receptive field response (OFF or ON) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "werblin1969organization,kaneko1970physiological"

\end_inset

 or by whether their synapses with photoreceptors were 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invaginating
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "missotten1965synapses,dowling1966organization"

\end_inset

.
 These classifications were initially thought to be related through observations
 in the cyprinid fish 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "famiglietti1977neuronal"

\end_inset

, but it was soon discovered in amphibians that the relationship was not
 universal [Lasansky 1978].
 Rodent work in the grey squirrel further cast doubt on the validity of
 the synaptic classification, as a class of BC in the squirrel retina was
 found to have both flat and invaginating synapses with cone photoreceptors
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "west1978bipolar"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Research in the late 1970s began to focus on classification using the depth
 of the stratification of the axonal arbor in the IPL 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "famiglietti1976structural"

\end_inset

.
 It was found that BCs with OFF centers stratify in the outer (proximal
 to the epithelium) region of the IPL, while BCs with ON centers stratify
 in the inner region.
 These outer and inner regions began to be referred to as subliminae a and
 b, respectively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nelson1978intracellular"

\end_inset

.
 The subdivision of BCs into more refined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

types
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 demonstrates significant species difference.
 In the rabbit, it was observed through the reconstruction of individual
 neurons in electron micrograph images and through golgi staining that there
 existed at least nine distinct BC morphologies within the subliminae 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "famiglietti1981functional,mills1992morphology"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ghosh:2004ff"

\end_inset

 extended this work to the mouse retina, wherein they identified nine cone
 BC types in addition to the rod BC using light microscopy with immunostaining
 to help distinguish cells with different receptor types.
 This classification was further refined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wassle2009cone"

\end_inset

 using additional immunocytochemical markers, revealing that Type 3 (BC3)
 as defined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ghosh:2004ff"

\end_inset

 consisted of two separate types, BC3a and BC3b.
 They also hypothesized that BC5 was in fact two cell types, which was later
 confirmed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

 through the dense reconstruction of electron micrograph images.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

 also identified a BC type that co-stratifies with the other BC5s, but has
 a wider lateral span and stratifies more narrowly in IPL depth, and they
 further speculated that there may exist a third BC5 type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The different types have been observed to have differing time lags in visual
 response.
 This is mostly characterized by a sustained verses transient response,
 rather than a latency difference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq,Borghuis:2013uq"

\end_inset

.
 While existing work has not yet conclusively determined which BC types
 show more sustained activity, evidence suggests that the IPL is subdivided
 not just into on and off regions, but that these sublamina are further
 subdivided into sustained and transient regions at the depths stratified
 by SACs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Direction selectivity in retinal ganglion cells
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among the earliest work in the study of the behavior of cells in the vertibrate
 retina was that of Hartline in his 1938 account.
 There it was discovered that there exists at least three types of retinal
 ganglion cells (GCs) that respond to different stimulus features.
 He identified ON cells that would respond to the onset of a light stimulus,
 OFF cells that would respond to the termination of light stimulation, and
 ON-OFF cells that respond to both the onset and termination of light.
 These observations were followed in the 1950s and early 1960s by several
 researchers, who demonstrated that there were units responding to more
 complicated features, such as convexity, dimming, and color specificity
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lettvin1959frog,wiesel1960receptive,wolbarsht1961receptive"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BARLOW:1964bh"

\end_inset

 were the first to discover directionally selective (DS) GCs.
 They observed a class of GC that responds to both ON and OFF stimuli that
 moves in a specific direction.
 While On-Off DSGCs come in four subtypes, one for a preference in each
 of the four cardinal directions, other DSGCs in the mouse have been identified
 that don't have such diversity.
 The On DSGC can have one of three preferred directions, while Off DSGCs,
 such as the ventral-preferring JAMB-cell, have been found that only ever
 prefer a single direction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2008kl"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The starburst amacrine cell
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 1980s, the starburst amacrine cell (SAC), a neuronal cell type in
 the mammalian retina, was discovered and characterized 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Famiglietti:1983kx"

\end_inset

.
 SAC dendrites receive excitatory input synapses from bipolar cells (BCs),
 which in turn receive input from photoreceptors.
 SAC dendrites also make synapses onto ganglion cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Famiglietti:1991fk"

\end_inset

, which send signals from the retina to the brain through the optic nerve.
 Like most other amacrine cells, SACs lack an axon; their output synapses
 are found in the distal zones of their dendrites.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two subtypes of SACs, one stratifying in the OFF sublayer of the
 IPL and one in the ON sublayer.
 The latter are sometimes called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

displaced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 SACs due to their somata appearing in the ganglion cell layer rather than
 the inner nuclear layer.
 The two types are morphologically very similar, although OFF SACs tend
 to be about 
\begin_inset Formula $15\%$
\end_inset

 larger than their ON counterparts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Research on the question of directional selectivity has converged upon SAC.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "borg1992model"

\end_inset

 observed that SAC dendrites could function as temporal delay lines, as
 time is required for current from input synapses to propagate to output
 synapses (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

c).
 They modeled SAC dendrites as passive electrical cables, and showed that
 temporal delays could lead to direction selectivity, as had been observed
 more generally by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rall1964theoretical"

\end_inset

.
 Their passive cable model can be approximated by a Reichardt detector,
 if BC input synapses onto an SAC dendrite are lumped into two groups: (1)
 proximal synapses near the soma, and (2) distal synapses near the dendritic
 tips and the output synapses (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

c).
 Since proximal synapses are the delayed input and distal synapses the nondelaye
d input, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "borg1992model"

\end_inset

 predicted that outward motion should activate SAC dendrites more than inward
 motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remarkably, their prediction of SAC direction selectivity was confirmed
 ten years later 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

, as well as their prediction of an outward 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preferred direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (PD).
 A SAC dendrite is more activated by motion outward from the cell body to
 the tip of the dendrite, than by motion in the opposite direction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore a SAC dendrite exhibits DS, and outward motion is said to be
 its 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preferred direction.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Note that it is incorrect to assign a single such direction to a SAC, because
 each of the cell's dendrites has its own preferred direction (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SACimg"

\end_inset

a).
 DS persists after blocking inhibitory synaptic transmission 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

, when the only remaining inputs to SACs are bipolar cells (BCs), which
 are excitatory.
 Since the SAC exhibits DS, while its BC inputs do not 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yonehara:2013hc"

\end_inset

, we say that DS 
\emph on
emerges
\emph default
 from the BC-SAC circuit.
 More recently, it was shown that BC inputs do not exhibit direction selectivity
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yonehara:2013hc"

\end_inset

, confirming their assumption that motion detection occurs somewhere between
 BCs and SACs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, an inconsistency with empirical data also emerged.
 According to the model, the soma should depolarize more for inward motion
 than for outward motion, i.e., have a PD opposite that of the distal dendrites
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

e).
 In fact, the PDs of the soma and distal zone turn out to be the same 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

.
 To resolve this inconsistency, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

 argued that active conductances must be added to the passive cable model
 of the SAC dendrite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inhibitory connections between SACs are also known to exist 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lee:2006qa"

\end_inset

, and can contribute to SAC direction selectivity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhou:2008kx"

\end_inset

.
 However, SAC-SAC inhibition does not appear necessary for direction selectivity
, which persists even during pharmacological blockade of inhibitory synaptic
 transmission 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore the present work focuses on BC-SAC circuitry.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename off_sac papers/SACpic.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Starburst Amacrine Cell.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SACimg"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An Off SAC.
 
\series bold
a
\series default
, View of an SAC on the plane perpindicular to the light axis.
 Each dendrite of the SAC has a separate preferred direction oriented outward
 from the soma.
 The inset shows vericosities in the distal regions of the dendrite, indicating
 likely presynaptic sites.
 
\series bold
b
\series default
, A view of the same SAC from a plane parallel to the light axis.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Existing Models of direction selectivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barlow1963selective"

\end_inset

 first direction selective ganglion cells, they believed that DS arose in
 these cells through lateral inhibition displaced toward the preferred direction.
 If inhibition passes through a temporal delay line, or the inhibitory signal
 is sustained for a longer duration than the excitatory signal, this displacemen
t could yield DS responses (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

b).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wyatt1975directionally"

\end_inset

 further investigated this theory and confirmed the hypothesis.
 They identified a cardioid-shaped inhibitory receptive field around each
 point of excitation on the DSGC, biased in the preferred direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another model exists that has appeared in models of biological motion detection
 since the 1950s, but has not previously been ascribed to a specific neural
 circuit in the mammalian visual system.
 Motion can be detected by correlating excitatory input signals from two
 locations, if one signal passes through a temporal delay line.
 Stimulation of the delayed input followed by the nondelayed input causes
 signals to arrive synchronously at the output element, and to activate
 it.
 Stimulation in the opposite order gives rise to asynchronous signals at
 the output element, and no activation.
 In honor of the pioneering researcher Werner Reichardt, we will refer to
 the computational motif of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

a as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Reichardt detector,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 although it is actually a subunit of his model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "reichardt1961autocorrelation"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The passive cable model of SAC direction selectivity is based on the assumption
 that the temporal delay in the Reichardt detector is due to propagation
 of signals within the SAC dendrites (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

d).
 This thesis explores another possibility: perhaps temporal delay could
 arise from mechanisms 
\emph on
presynaptic
\emph default
 to SAC dendrites (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

c), since mouse BCs have been classified into multiple types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wassle2009cone"

\end_inset

, which are known to have distinct temporal behaviors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq,Borghuis:2013uq"

\end_inset

.
 If the connectivity of BC types with SACs varied with distance from the
 SAC soma, the BC-SAC circuit could end up resembling 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

c.
 We tested this hypothesis by reconstructing BC-SAC circuitry using e2198,
 a dataset of mouse retinal images from serial block-face scanning electron
 microscopy (SBEM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Briggman:2011zr"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Motion is a spatiotemporal phenomenon: an object at one location appears
 somewhere else after a time delay.
 Therefore we wondered whether DS might arise because different locations
 on the SAC dendrite are wired to BC types with different time lags.
 More specifically, we hypothesized that the proximal BCs (wired near the
 SAC soma) lag the distal BCs (wired far from the soma).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space-time wiring specificity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 could lead to DS as follows (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

c).
 Motion outward from the soma will activate the proximal BCs followed by
 the distal BCs.
 If the stimulus speed is appropriate for the time lag, signals from both
 BC groups will reach the SAC dendrite simultaneously, summing to produce
 a large depolarization.
 For motion inward towards the soma, BC signals will reach the SAC dendrite
 asynchronously, causing only small depolarizations.
 Therefore the dendrite will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prefer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 outward motion, as observed experimentally 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename DSmech.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hypothesized Models of Direction Selectivity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
General and SAC-specific models of DS.
 
\series bold
a
\series default
, A schematic representation of the Reichardt model.
 The two arms represent two spatially distinct excitatory inputs, with the
 input of the left arm being delayed relative to the right arm.
 If the detector is active only when it receives two simultaneous inputs,
 a stimulus moving from left to right in time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 will activate the detector, while a stimulus moving in the opposite direction
 will not.
 
\series bold
b
\series default
, Similarly, the Barlow-Levick model has two arms with a delay line, but
 in this model, the delay is on the right arm, which provides inhibitory
 input rather than excitatory.
 If the detector is active only when it receives excitation without simultaneous
ly receiving inhibition, once again only the rightward traveling stimulus
 will active the detector.
 
\series bold
c
\series default
, A Reichardt-like mechanism for DS in the SAC, with the delay line occuring
 presynaptically 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tukker2004direction"

\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
d
\series default
, The same model, but with a postsynaptic delay line via intracellular signal
 propagation.
 
\series bold
e
\series default
, An illustration of the observation that if there is a delay occuring through
 signal propagation, a stimulus traveling in the null direction should cause
 substantial depolarization in the soma, contrary to empirical observations
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Reconstruction of the Retina by Man and Machine
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
30 years ago, John Graham White, under the supervision of Sydney Brenner,
 undertook the heroic task of reconstructing the connectome of a tiny worm
 known as caenorhabditis elegans
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "White:1986uq"

\end_inset

.
 He recognized that only electron micrography offered the resolution necessary
 to positively identify synaptic contacts, as demonstrated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:resolutionImportant"

\end_inset

.
 After a decade of labor, White produced the first connectome through almost
 entirely manual reconstruction.
 In some case, neural processes were even printed, and physical reconstructions
 were created as a means of visualization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Happily, the development of modern computers allows us to substantially
 improve upon the reconstruction rate of White et al.
 We reconstructed e2198, an existing dataset of mouse retinal images from
 serial block-face scanning electron microscopy (SBEM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Briggman:2011zr"

\end_inset

.
 The size of the data is approximately 350 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

 x 350 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

 x 50 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

, with the final dimension being parallel to the light axis.
 e2198 is located in the ventral portion of the retinal at a depth such
 that it spans the IPL and includes a portion of the INL and GCL.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename off_sac papers/Seung_EDfig8.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The value of resolution.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:resolutionImportant"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Frameless
