 onto the 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 plane.
 Due to the sparse representation of BC8/9 in our set of reconstructed cells,
 we were unable to subdivide it.
 
\series bold
d
\series default
, BC5t and BC5o are differentiated by stratification thickness, as defined
 by the difference between a cell's 85th and 25th percentile IPL depths.
 
\series bold
e
\series default
, BC5i and XBC differ in the total area of their projection onto the 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 plane.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
mouse BCs were originally classified into nine cone types (BC1 through BC9)
 and one rod type based on light microscopic anatomy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ghosh:2004ff"

\end_inset

.
 Later on, BC3 was subdivided into BC3a and BC3b based on molecular differences
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wassle2009cone"

\end_inset

.
 Then electron microscopic anatomy was used to distinguish BC3a and BC3b,
 divide BC5 into two types, and discover a new XBC type 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We revisited the classification of On BCs using the e2198 reconstructions
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:on-bc-class"

\end_inset

).
 As shown in the gallery of example cells (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

a, b), On BC axons are found in half the depth of the IPL, closer to the
 GCL than the INL.
 Our On BC types correspond to those defined previously, with good agreement
 regarding densities (compare Fig.
 3D with Fig.
 1E inset of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

).
 The novelty is the subdivision of BC5 into three types called BC5t, BC5i,
 and BC5o.
 The three types stratify at similar depths (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

a, c), which is why they were originally grouped into a single Type 5 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ghosh:2004ff"

\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, it is possible to differentiate between the types based on
 subtle differences between their stratification profiles.
 BC5-inner (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

BC5i
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) stratifies slightly more towards the inner retina than the other types
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

a, b and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:on-bc-class"

\end_inset

b).
 BC5-thick (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

BC5t
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is more thickly stratified than BC5-outer (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

BC5o
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

a, c and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:on-bc-class"

\end_inset

d.
 The stratification profile of BC5t is weakly bimodal (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

c), but this property was not used for the classification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are confident of our three-way division of BC5 based on stratification
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:on-bc-class"

\end_inset

1), because the axonal arbors of each cluster end up roughly tiling the
 retina with little overlap (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

e, f, g).
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tiling principle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is thought to be a defining characteristic of a true bipolar cell type
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wassle2009cone"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, when BC5 cells are divided into just two clusters, it
 is impossible to avoid many collisions between highly overlapping axonal
 arbors (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:connectivity-bc5"

\end_inset

e).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only a few violations of the tiling principle are evident in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

e, f, and g.
 One possibility is that the tiling principle holds only approximately,
 and that the violations are a form of biological 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Another possibility is that the violations result from errors in our classifica
tion procedure.
 Therefore, we generated a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corrected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 classification by swapping a few cells between types.
 The number of swaps is relatively small.
 The corrected classification was the basis of subsequent analysis of BC-SAC
 wiring, but our results are qualitatively unchanged even if the uncorrected
 classification is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

