\begin_layout Plain Layout
Alternative contact analysis based on total areas rather than averages over
 individual pairs.
 
\series bold
a,
\series default
 Total contact observed between all reconstructed BCs and SACs as a function
 of distance from the SAC soma.
 
\series bold
b, 
\series default
Total SAC surface area within the union of convex hulls of each BC type
 as a function of distance from the SAC soma.
 All graphs are peaked around 80 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m, which is the region of maximum SAC dendritic branching.
 The sharp decrease at larger distances is due to thinning and termination
 of SAC branches.
 The graphs differ across BC types, because the types do not cover exactly
 the same retinal areas.
 
\series bold
c, 
\series default
Fraction of SAC surface area in contact with BC types, estimated by dividing
 contact area (
\series bold
a
\series default
) by SAC surface area (
\series bold
b
\series default
).
 This estimate is similar to that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d, but lacks error bars.
 
\series bold
d,
\series default
 Fraction of SAC surface area contacted by all BC types, obtained as the
 sum of the contact fractions in (
\series bold
c
\series default
).
 Also plotted for comparison is the contact predicted by co-stratification,
 the sum of the curves from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

b.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Co-stratification analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Off SACs stratify at a particular depth in the IPL (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a).
 Why this depth and not some other? From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

a, it is obvious that this depth is appropriate for wiring with BC2 and
 BC3a, as required by our model of DS emergence.
 Following this logic one step further, we wondered whether the observed
 dependence of contact on distance from the SAC soma might be reflected
 in fine aspects of SAC morphology.
 We hypothesized that SAC dendrites are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tilted,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 moving deeper into the IPL with distance from the SAC soma.
 Such a change in depth would be compatible with more overlap with BC2 near
 the soma, and more overlap with BC3a far from the soma, since BC3a is deeper
 in the IPL than BC2 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hypothesized tilt turns out to exist (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a).
 Very close to the SAC soma, the dendrites dive sharply into the IPL from
 the INL.
 Surprisingly, IPL depth continues to increase as distance from the SAC
 soma in the tangential plane ranges from 20 to 80 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

m.
 The slight increase is not evident in a single dendrite, but emerges from
 statistical averaging.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Could dendritic tilt be the cause of the observed variation in BC-SAC contact
 with distance (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d)? We cannot address causality based on our data, but we can test how well
 the tilt predicts contact variation.
 We computed the stratification profiles of BC types (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a), defined as the one-dimensional density of BC surface area along the
 depth of the IPL.
 We also computed the stratification profile of SAC dendrites at various
 distances from the SAC soma (quartiles, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a).
 Assuming that BC and SAC arbors are statistically independent of each other,
 we estimated contact from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

co-stratification,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 defined as the integral over IPL depth of the product of BC and SAC stratificat
ion profiles (Methods).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found that actual BC2 contact depends more strongly on distance than
 predicted; the slight change in IPL depth after the initial plunge appears
 too small to account for the large change in actual BC2 contact.
 In other failures of contact prediction, BC3a, BC3b, and BC4 stratify at
 the same IPL depths (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a), yet BC3a makes much more contact than BC3b or BC4.
 Also, actual BC3a contact plummets near the tips of SAC dendrites (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d), while predicted contact does not change at all because the IPL depth
 of SAC dendrites is constant in this region (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

b).
 Overall, the total contact from all BC types seems low in this region (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Alternative-contact-OFF"

\end_inset

d), suggesting that BCs avoid making synaptic inputs to the most distal
 SAC dendrites.
 This runs counter to the conventional belief that input synapses are uniformly
 distributed over the entire length of SAC dendrites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Famiglietti:1991fk"

\end_inset

.
 The unreliability of inferring contact from co-stratification is illustrated
 by numerous examples of SAC dendrites that pass through BC axonal arbors
 without making any contact at all (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:resolutionImportant"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename off_sac papers/figure5.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
BC-SAC co-stratification.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
a
\series default
, SAC dendrites move deeper into the IPL (median depth, red line) with increasin
g distance from the SAC soma in the tangential plane.
 Stratification profiles of BC types, defined as density of surface area
 over the depth of the IPL.
 
\series bold
b
\series default
, Co-stratification predictions of BC-SAC contact area vs.
 distance from the SAC soma.
 The curves are normalized by SAC area at each distance, and are therefore
 directly comparable with those of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To perform these analyses, all SAC surface voxels were binned by distance
 from the soma center in the SAC plane.
 Within each bin, the stratification profile was computed as for the BCs.
 The quartiles (median and 
\begin_inset Formula $25$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $75$
\end_inset

th percentiles) are graphed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a.
 The prediction of contact from co-stratification is based on the following
 formalism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the arbor density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{a}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 as the surface area per unit volume at location 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

 of a type 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 cell with soma centered at the origin.
 Its integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int d^{3}r\,\rho_{a}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 is the total surface area of the arbor.
 We assume that the contact density received by one cell of type 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 from all cells of type 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{ab}(\vec{r})=\rho_{a}(\vec{r})\sum_{i}\rho_{b}(\vec{r}-\vec{r}_{bi})\label{eq:ContactDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The sum over the 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 mosaic can be approximated by a function that is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\rho_{b}(\vec{r}-\vec{r}_{bi})\approx\sigma_{b}s_{b}(z)\label{eq:MosaicSum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the number of type 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 neurons per retinal area and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{b}(z)=\int dxdy\,\rho_{b}(x,y,z)\label{eq:StratificationArborDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the stratification profile of a cell of type 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The SAC arbor density is assumed radially symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{SAC}(\vec{r})=\rho_{SAC}\left(\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}},z\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be regarded (up to normalization) as the SAC stratification profile
 as a function of distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}$
\end_inset

 from the SAC soma.
 Integrating the contact density (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ContactDensity"

\end_inset

) and normalizing yields the fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}(r)$
\end_inset

 of SAC area contacted by cell type 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{b}(r)=\sigma_{b}\frac{\int dz\:\rho_{SAC}(r,z)s_{b}(z)}{\int dz\:\rho_{SAC}(r,z)}\label{eq:FractionalContactArea}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model of direction selectivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imaging of intracellular calcium in BC axons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq"

\end_inset

 and extracellular glutamate around BC axons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Borghuis:2013uq"

\end_inset

 indicate that BC2 lags BC3a in visual responses by 50 to 100 ms.
 Therefore BC-SAC wiring appears to possess the space-time specificity appropria
te for an outward preferred direction, as we hypothesize (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

c).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another important difference between BC2 and BC3a: BC3a responds
 more transiently to step changes in illumination, while BC2 exhibits more
 sustained responses.
 The implications of the sustained-transient distinction for DS can be understoo
d using a mathematical model.
 The activity of a retinal neuron is often approximated as a linear spatiotempor
al filtering of the visual stimulus followed by a nonlinearity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Berry:1998kx,Baccus:2002vn"

\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

linear-nonlinear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model for the output 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset

 of the SAC dendrite can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O(t)=\left[\int dxdt'\:W(x,t-t')I(x,t')\right]^{+}\label{eq:LinearNonlinear}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For simplicity, the dendrite and visual stimulus 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,t)$
\end_inset

 are restricted to a single spatial dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and the nonlinearity is a half-wave rectification, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[z\right]^{+}=\max\left\{ z,0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We interpret the integral in Eq.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LinearNonlinear"

\end_inset

) as the summed input from the BCs presynaptic to the SAC.
 The nonlinearity could arise from various biophysical mechanisms, such
 as synaptic transmission from SACs to other neurons.
 The spatiotemporal filter 
\begin_inset Formula $W(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is a sum of two functions, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W(x,t)=U_{s}(x)v_{s}(t)+U_{t}(x)v_{t}(t)\label{eq:SumTwoSeparableFilters}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

corresponding to contributions from BC2 and BC3a.
 The sustained temporal filter 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}(t)$
\end_inset

 is monophasic, while the transient filter 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}(t)$
\end_inset

 is biphasic (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

a).
 The spatial filter 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{s}(x)$
\end_inset

 represents the entire set of all BC2 inputs to the dendrite, and can be
 estimated from the BC2 contact area graph in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{t}(x)$
\end_inset

 can be estimated from the BC3a contact area graph.
 The two spatial filters are displaced relative to each other (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

a), because BC3a tends to contact SAC dendrites at more distal locations
 than BC2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well known that direction selectivity (DS) can be generated by a model
 like Eqs.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LinearNonlinear"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SumTwoSeparableFilters"

\end_inset

), which is based on the sum of two space-time separable filters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Watson:1985fk,Adelson:1985bh"

\end_inset

.
 This is illustrated by Fig.
 6 using the fact that the convolution in Eq.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LinearNonlinear"

\end_inset

) is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sliding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the spatiotemporal filter 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 in time over the stimulus 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, and computing the overlap at each time.
 The filter 
\begin_inset Formula $W(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is oriented in space-time (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

a), and so also is a moving stimulus 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,t)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

g,h).
 The overlap with a rightward-moving stimulus (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

h) is greater than for a leftward one (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

g), so the model is DS, and rightward is the preferred direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How is DS affected by the biphasic shape of the transient temporal filter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}(t)$
\end_inset

? If we remove the negative lobe (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

c), then 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}(t)$
\end_inset

 will become monophasic like 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}(t)$
\end_inset

 and their relation closer to a simple time lag (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

d).
 We will refer to this model as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Reichardt detector,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in honor of the pioneering researcher Werner Reichardt, although it more
 closely resembles a subunit of his model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "reichardt1961autocorrelation"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, removing the positive lobe of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}(t)$
\end_inset

 makes it monophasic but with inverted sign relative to the sustained filter
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

e).
 The result (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

f) resembles a DS model originally proposed by Barlow and Levick 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Barlow:1965dq"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both modified models (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

d,f) exhibit DS.
 In the Reichardt detector, the inputs from the two arms enhance each other
 for motion in the preferred direction.
 In the Barlow-Levick detector, the two inputs cancel each other for motion
 in the null direction.
 Since our sustained-transient model (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

b) employs both mechanisms, it should exhibit more DS than either detector.
 Our model is related to versions of the Reichardt detector with low-pass
 and high-pass filters on the two arms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Borst:2003fk"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the original Barlow-Levick model, the negative filter corresponded to
 synaptic inhibition.
 Since BCs are believed to be excitatory, negative BC input in our model
 represents a reduction of excitation relative to the resting level, rather
 than true inhibition.
 Signaling by reduced excitation may be possible, at least for low contrast
 stimuli, as BC ribbon synapses may have a significant resting rate of transmitt
er release 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lagnado:1996fk"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model of Eqs.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LinearNonlinear"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SumTwoSeparableFilters"

\end_inset

) is a useful starting point for many theoretical investigations that are
 outside the scope of this article.
 For example, DS dependences on the spatial and temporal frequency of a
 sinusoidal traveling wave stimulus are calculated in the Supplementary
 Equations, and DS dependence on stimulus speed is graphed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Model-direction-selectivity"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename off_sac papers/figure6.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Mathematical model of the BC-SAC circuit.

\series bold
 
