\series default
, Removing the positive channel yields a Barlow-Levick detector (
\series bold
f
\series default
).
 A moving visual stimulus 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is oriented in space-time (
\series bold
g
\series default
, 
\series bold
h
\series default
), and so are the spatiotemporal filters (
\series bold
a
\series default
, 
\series bold
c
\series default
, 
\series bold
e
\series default
).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Mathematical model of the BC-SAC circuit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output 
\begin_inset Formula $O(t)$
\end_inset

 of a SAC dendrite is modeled as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O(t)=g\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}c_{i}f_{i}\left(\int dxdt'w_{i}(x,t-t')I(x,t')\right)\right)\label{eq:Cascade}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The dendrite and the visual stimulus 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,t)$
\end_inset

 are restricted for simplicity to a single spatial dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th BC filters the visual stimulus with 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}(x,t)$
\end_inset

, and the result is passed through the nonlinear function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The contributions from the BCs are weighted by the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}<0$
\end_inset

, summed, and passed through a nonlinear function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(z)=\left[z+b_{i}\right]^{+}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 corresponding to spontaneous output in the absence of visual stimulation.
 Then the BC output nonlinearity can be neglected for visual stimuli with
 sufficiently small amplitude.
 Also suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)=\left[z-a\right]^{+}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a threshold for SAC response, or some source of spontaneous
 inhibitory input.
 Then Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Cascade"

\end_inset

) simplifies to 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O(t)=\left[\int dxdt'\sum_{i=1}^{n}c_{i}w_{i}(x,t-t')I(x,t')+\sum_{i}b_{i}c_{i}-a\right]^{+}\label{eq:LN-model-with-offset}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now assume that each spatiotemporal filter is separable, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}(x,t)\approx u_{i}(x)v_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

, and that each temporal filter is either sustained or transient, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}(t)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}c_{i}w_{i}(x,t)\approx U_{s}(x)v_{s}(t)+U_{t}(x)v_{t}(t)\label{eq:LN-model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{s}(x)=\sum_{i\in S}c_{i}u_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{t}(x)=\sum_{i\in T}c_{i}u_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the weighted sums of spatial filters over the sustained and transient
 sets of BCs.
 Finally, Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LN-model-with-offset"

\end_inset

) reduces to Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LN-model"

\end_inset

) if 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\sum_{i}b_{i}c_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the visual stimulus is a sinusoidal traveling wave, 
\begin_inset Formula $I(x,t)=\cos(kx-\omega t)$
\end_inset

, then the integral in Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LN-model"

\end_inset

) yields a sine wave given by the real part of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\tilde{u}_{s}(k)\tilde{v}_{s}(\omega)+\tilde{u}_{t}(k)\tilde{v}_{t}(\omega)\right]e^{-i\omega t} & = & \tilde{u}_{s}(k)\tilde{v}_{s}(\omega)\left[1-i\omega\tau e^{ik\Delta x}\right]e^{-i\omega t}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}_{s}(k)=\int dx\,e^{ikx}u_{s}(x)$
\end_inset

 and other Fourier transforms are defined similarly.
 The amplitude of the sine wave defines the peak and time-averaged response
 of Eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LN-model"

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
A(k,\omega) & = & \left|\tilde{u}_{s}(k)\right|\left|\tilde{v}_{s}(\omega)\right|\left|1-i\omega\tau e^{ik\Delta x}\right|\\
 & = & \left|\tilde{u}_{s}(k)\right|\left|\tilde{v}_{s}(\omega)\right|\sqrt{1+2\omega\tau\sin k\Delta x+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The term linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the DS component of the response.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x>0$
\end_inset

 without loss of generality, the preferred direction (PD) is rightward for
 spatial frequencies satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|k\Delta x\right|<\pi$
\end_inset

.
 Outside this range, spatial aliasing can cause the PD to reverse.
 The direction selectivity index (DSI) is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
DSI & = & \frac{PD-ND}{PD}=1-\sqrt{\frac{1-2\omega\tau\left|\sin k\Delta x\right|+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}{1+2\omega\tau\left|\sin k\Delta x\right|+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
DSI=\frac{PD-ND}{PD}=1-\sqrt{\frac{1-2\omega\tau\left|\sin k\Delta x\right|+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}{1+2\omega\tau\left|\sin k\Delta x\right|+\left(\omega\tau\right)^{2}}}\label{eq:DSI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which can be rewritten as Eq.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DSI"

\end_inset

) in the main text.
 This is a periodic function of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, because the DSI is a ratio of responses.
 The responses themselves will typically vanish for large 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, due to the spatial filtering, but the DSI is independent of the filter
 functions.
 According to the second line, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq DSI\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 The third line is maximized for any fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $k\Delta x=\pi/2$
\end_inset

.
 This means that an optimal wavelength for the stimulus is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=4\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
DSI=1-\frac{1-\omega\tau}{1+\omega\tau}
\]

\end_inset

which in turn is maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\tau=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename off_sac papers/Seung_EDfig9.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Model direction selectivity index (DSI) versus stimulus speed.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Model-direction-selectivity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
DSI versus stimulus speed (units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x/\tau$
\end_inset

) for traveling sine waves of various wavelengths 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

).
 The preferred speed (horizontal location of each peak) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda/(2\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that responses are cut off at high speeds by the temporal filters
 of the model, but the DSI can decay more slowly.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our DS model, SAC dendrites are wired to BC types with different time
 lags.
 A previous model did not distinguish between BC types, and instead relied
 on the time lag of signal conduction within the SAC dendrite itself 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tukker2004direction"

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

d).
 Like most other amacrine cells, SACs lack an axon; their output synapses
 are found in the distal zones of their dendrites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Famiglietti:1991fk"

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Off-SAC-(red)"

\end_inset

a, inset).
 Due to dendritic conduction delay, proximal BC inputs should take longer
 to reach the output synapses than distal BC inputs (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

d).
 Therefore this time lag is also consistent with the empirical finding of
 an outward preferred direction.
 To summarize the novelty of our hypothesis, we place the time lag before
 BC-SAC synapses, whereas the previous model places it after BC-SAC synapses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The postsynaptic delay model has a major weakness.
 If dendritic conduction were the only source of time lag, the somatic voltage
 would exhibit DS with an inward preferred direction, but this is inconsistent
 with intracellular recordings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

 (Fig.
 1e).
 In contrast, the presynaptic delay model is compatible with approximating
 an SAC dendrite as isopotential (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hypothesized-Models-of"

\end_inset

c), so preferred direction is predicted to be independent of the location
 of the voltage measurement, consistent with empirical data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

.
 It may also be possible to make the postsynaptic delay model consistent
 with experiments by adding active dendritic conductances 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presynaptic and postsynaptic delay models are not mutually exclusive.
 If they work together, passive cable theory suggests that presynaptic delay
 dominates, because estimated postsynaptic delay is much shorter than the
 time lag between BC2 and BC3a (Supplementary Equations).
 Can we gauge the relative importance of the delays empirically rather than
 theoretically? One way would be intracellular recording at the SAC soma
 of responses to visual stimulation at various dendritic locations.
 If postsynaptic delay dominates, then response latency will grow with distance
 of the visual stimulus from the soma.
 If presynaptic delay dominates, then distal stimulation will evoke somatic
 responses with shorter latency than proximal stimulation.
 This prediction may seem counterintuitive, but is an obvious outcome of
 our model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many other models of DS emergence in SACs invoke inhibition as well as excitatio
n 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "borg1992model,Gavrikov:2003om,Munch:2006qy,Lee:2006qa"

\end_inset

.
 We have focused on excitatory mechanisms, as blocking inhibition does not
 abolish DS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Euler:2002oq"

\end_inset

.
 However, inhibition may have the effect of enhancing DS, and its role should
 be investigated further.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work focused on Off BC-SAC circuitry.
 An analogous sustained-transient distinction can also be made for On BC
 types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq,Borghuis:2013uq"

\end_inset

.
 It remains to be seen whether their connectivity with On SACs depends on
 distance from the soma.
 If this turns out to be the case, then the model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

 could serve as a general theory of motion detection by both On and Off
 SACs.
 The model filter of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sac-model"

\end_inset

a also resembles the spatiotemporal receptive field of the J type of ganglion
 cell (Fig.
 3b of Ref.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kim:2008kl"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neural activity imaging 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Maisak:2013ly"

\end_inset

 and connectomic analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Takemura:2013zr"

\end_inset

 have recently identified a plausible candidate for the site of DS emergence
 in the fly visual system.
 If our theory is correct, then the analogies between insect and mammalian
 motion detection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Borst:2011vn"

\end_inset

 are more far-reaching than previously suspected, with fly T4 and T5 cells
 corresponding to On and Off SAC dendrites in both connectivity and function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A glimmer of space-time wiring specificity can even be seen in the structure
 of the SAC itself.
 Since BC types with different time lags arborize at different IPL depths,
 IPL depth can be regarded as a time axis.
 Therefore, the slight tilt of the SAC dendrites in the IPL (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-costrat"

\end_inset

a) could be related to the orientation of the SAC receptive field in space-time
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Model-direction-selectivity"

\end_inset

a).
 However, dendritic tilt alone is not sufficient to predict our model, as
 co-stratification sometimes fails to predict contact (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

b).
 For example, co-stratification predicts strong BC4 connectivity to distal
 SAC dendrites.
 This would favor an inward preferred direction, contrary to what is observed,
 because BC2 leads (not lags) BC4 in visual responses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea that contact (or connectivity) can be inferred from co-stratification
 is sometimes known as Peters' Rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "braitenberg1998cortex"

\end_inset

, and has also been applied to estimate neocortical connectivity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kalisman:2003vn,Binzegger:2004kl,Stepanyants:2005kx"

\end_inset

.
 The present work shows that fairly subtle violations of Peters' Rule may
 be important for visual function.
 Previous research suggests that On-Off direction selective ganglion cells
 (DSGCs) inherit their DS from SAC inputs due to a strong violation of Peters'
 Rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fried:2002mi,yonehara2010spatially,wei2010development,Briggman:2011zr"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our findings were made possible by using AI to reduce the amount of human
 effort required for 3D reconstruction of neurons.
 Even after the labor savings, our research required great human effort
 from a handful of paid workers in the lab and a large number of volunteers
 through EyeWire.
 Our experiences do not support claims that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wisdom of the crowd
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should replace experts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "surowiecki2005wisdom"

\end_inset

.
 Instead, EyeWire depends on cooperation between lab experts and online
 amateurs (Methods).
 Furthermore, some amateurs developed remarkable expertise and were promoted
 to increasingly sophisticated roles within the EyeWire community (Supplementary
 Notes).
 We believe that crowd wisdom requires amplifying the expert voices within
 the crowd, and also empowering individuals to become experts.
 Fortunately, such goals are well-matched to the game format.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The EyeWire AI was based on a deep convolutional network 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "TuragaMALIS09,Turaga:2010ij"

\end_inset

.
 Similar networks have been successfully applied to serial EM images obtained
 using conventional staining techniques that mark intracellular organelles
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ciresan2012deep"

\end_inset

.
 Extending EyeWire to such images, in which synapses are clearly visible,
 would enable a true connection analysis that goes beyond the contact and
 co-stratification analyses employed here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our work demonstrates that reconstructing a neural circuit can provide surprisin
g insights into its function.
 Much more will be learned as reconstruction speed grows.
 The combination of crowd and artificial intelligence promises a continuous
 upward path of improvement, as human input from the crowd is not only useful
 for generating neuroscience discoveries, but also for making the AI more
 capable through machine learning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Analagous Connectivity in the On SAC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starburst amacrine cell (SAC) is a key player in retinal computation
 of the direction of a moving stimulus.
 Ablation of SACs impairs the optokinetic reflex, a behavior that depends
 on computation of visual motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yoshida:2001rz,amthor2002effects"

\end_inset

.
 Both ablation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yoshida:2001rz,amthor2002effects"

\end_inset

 and reversible inactivation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vlasits:2014aa"

\end_inset

 of SACs reduce direction selective (DS) responses in ganglion cells, which
 receive synaptic input from SACs.
 SAC dendrites are preferentially activated by visual stimuli that move
 outward from the soma to the dendritic tips 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq,Lee:2006qa,Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed mechanisms for DS of SAC dendrites fall into several categories.
 According to inhibitory cellular hypotheses, dendritic biophysics causes
 inhibitory input to SACs to have effects that depend on dendritic location
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "borg1992model,Gavrikov:2003om"

\end_inset

.
 In inhibitory circuit hypotheses, GABAergic synaptic connectivity between
 SAC dendrites depends on the difference between their preferred directions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lee:2006qa,Munch:2006qy"

\end_inset

.
 In excitatory cellular hypotheses, SAC biophysics causes excitatory input
 to SACs to have effects that depend on dendritic location 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tukker2004direction,Hausselt:2007nx,Oesch:2010aa"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently we proposed a novel excitatory circuit hypothesis based on specificity
 of wiring between bipolar cells (BCs) and SACs.
 The proposal was based on anatomical evidence that sustained and transient
 BC types are connected to SACs at locations that are near and far from
 the SAC soma, respectively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2014sf"

\end_inset

.
 Such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space-time wiring specificity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 could make the BC-SAC circuit function as a correlation-type motion detector
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Borst:2011vn"

\end_inset

, and is consistent with the observed outward preferred direction of SAC
 dendrites.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like many other retinal neurons, the SAC comes in both On and Off types.
 The On SAC resembles a reflection of the Off SAC across a plane through
 the middle of the inner plexiform layer (IPL) (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

b, d).
 Probably due to this striking symmetry, DS and its mechanisms are often
 assumed to be similar between On and Off SACs.
 This remains merely an assumption as published studies of SACs were typically
 restricted to a single type.
 Physiological studies of DS were carried out for On SACs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Euler:2002oq,Lee:2006qa,Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

, while our anatomical study of BC-SAC wiring specificity was carried out
 for Off SACs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2014sf"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we find evidence that the On BC-SAC circuit possesses a space-time
 wiring specificity analogous to that shown previously for the Off BC-SAC
 circuit.
 We reconstructed a large set of On BCs and On SACs from e2198, a dataset
 of mouse retinal images from serial block-face scanning electron microscopy
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Briggman:2011zr"

\end_inset

.
 Based on the resulting high-resolution information about the anatomy of
 single cells, we have succeeded in subdividing BC5 into three types that
 we call BC5t, BC5i, and BC5o.
 This finding confirms a speculation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

, who were previously able to distinguish just two BC5 types, but predicted
 the existence of more.
 Our definition of a third BC5 type increases the total count of cone BC
 types to 13.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contact analysis is consistent with a wiring diagram in which BC7 prefers
 to synapse closer to the On SAC soma, and BC5 prefers to synapse farther
 from the soma (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

c).
 Among the BC5 types, synaptic input from BC5o is likely to be less than
 from BC5t and BC5i.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the available evidence suggests that transient BC types generally
 arborize near the IPL center, and sustained BC types near the IPL edges
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq,Borghuis:2013uq"

\end_inset

.
 (But see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Ichinose:2014aa"

\end_inset

 for a divergent view.) Combined with the standard division of the IPL into
 On and Off sublamina, this yields four sublayers: On-sustained, On-transient,
 Off-transient, and Off-sustained (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

b).
 Based on this IPL organization, it is likely that BC7 is sustained and
 BC5 is transient.
 If this is the case, then On BC-SAC wiring is analogous to Off BC-SAC wiring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figure1.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
