\begin_layout Section
BC-SAC contact analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We computed contact area between SACs and BCs of each type.
 The absolute areas were normalized to produce an estimate of the percentage
 of SAC surface area covered by BCs of each type (Experimental Procedures).
 This contact analysis suggests that BC5t, BC5i, and BC7 are likely the
 dominant bipolar cell inputs to the On SAC (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

a, c).
 Our result is consistent with previous anatomical reconstructions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

 and physiological experiments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Duan:2014rr,Chen:2014xy"

\end_inset

, though these previous studies did not distinguish all three BC5 types.
 If there is BC5o input, it is likely substantially weaker than BC5t and
 BC5i input (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To characterize the spatial relations between contacting cells, we examined
 the dependence of BC-SAC contact on distance between the BC axon and the
 SAC soma (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

b).
 The absolute areas were normalized to estimate the percentage of SAC surface
 area covered by BCs of a given type at a particular distance from the SAC
 soma (Experimental Procedures).
 The resulting graphs show that BC7 prefers to contact On SAC dendrites
 near the SAC soma, whereas BC5t and BC5i prefer to contact at an intermediate
 distance from the soma (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

c).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We only reconstructed BCs in the central area of e2198 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

e), and even within this area some BCs may have been missed (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

e, f, g).
 In our previous paper, we described methods of analyzing BC-SAC contact
 that are robust to both kinds of incompleteness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2014sf"

\end_inset

.
 The same methods were applied here, with only minor changes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compute each SAC's total contact area with all BCs of a given type divided
 by the SAC's surface area contained in the convex hull of the same BCs.
 This yields an estimate of the fraction of the SAC's surface in contact
 with BCs of the given type.
 This fraction is averaged over SACs to yield the estimates shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

A, with standard error based on the number of SACs that intersect the convex
 hull of the given BC type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each BC type, a coverage factor is computed by dividing the sum of hull
 areas for cells of the given type by the area of the union of hulls of
 the cells.
 The coverage factor represents the extent to which neighboring BCs of the
 same type overlap one another.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each BC-SAC pair, we compute the contact area divided by the surface
 area of the SAC within the convex hull of the BC.
 Multiplying by the coverage factor for the BC type yields an estimate of
 the fraction of the SAC's surface area contacting the BC type at that distance
 from that SAC's soma.
 This computation is done for all BC-SAC pairs, except that we discard pairs
 for which the BC hull contains fewer than 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 SAC surface voxels in order to dampen fluctuations.
 We bin the remaining BC-SAC pairs by distance and by BC type.
 For each bin and for each SAC that contributes pairs to that bin, we compute
 the mean over BC-SAC pairs.
 Each data point in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

c represents the mean of the SAC-specific means for that bin, and standard
 error is based on the number of SACs that contribute to that bin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One might worry that our contact analyses are sensitive to incomplete reconstruc
tion of BCs (see 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the tilings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Classification-of-On"

\end_inset

e, f, g).
 To avoid this problem, the results of our analyses are expressed not as
 absolute contact areas but instead as fractions of SAC surface area.
 To demonstrate robustness, we repeated our contact analyses after deleting
 a random subset of BC5t and BC5i cells (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Robustness-of-Contact"

\end_inset

a, b, c).
 The estimates of SAC coverage turned out virtually unchanged (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Robustness-of-Contact"

\end_inset

d, e); SAC coverage by BC5o was still much lower than by BC5t and BC5i.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contact analysis was done with BC types given by hierarchical clustering
 after a small number of swaps to correct for tiling violations, as explained
 above.
 The results of the contact analysis look similar if the tiling swaps are
 not performed (data not shown).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename supp_figure2.eps

\end_inset


