\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our reconstruction of the On BC-SAC circuit suggests that its wiring diagram
 parallels that of the Off BC-SAC circuit (Fig.
 1C).
 We find that sustained BC types prefer to contact SAC dendrites near the
 SAC soma, and transient BC types prefer an intermediate distance from the
 SAC soma.
 We interpret these contact preferences as reflecting synaptic connectivity
 preferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spatial organization of the IPL has previously been interpreted as supportin
g rules of wiring specificity.
 For example, the division of the IPL into On and Off sublayers (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

a) supports On to On and Off to Off rules for wiring of BCs to ganglion
 cells (GCs) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Famiglietti:1976aa,pang2003light"

\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the division of the IPL into sustained and transient sublayers
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

b) could support sustained to sustained and transient to transient rules
 of BC-GC wiring 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Awatramani:2000aa"

\end_inset

.
 Here the BC-SAC wiring diagram provides an explanation of why On and Off
 SACs are located at the boundaries between sustained and transient IPL
 sublayers (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

b).
 Namely, this positioning is appropriate for receiving convergent input
 from both sustained and transient BC types (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:On-Off-shematics"

\end_inset

c).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also find three differences between the On and Off circuits.
 First, BC7 and BC5i/t prefer to contact closer to the On SAC soma than
 their analogs BC2 and BC3a contact to the Off SAC soma (compare 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Wiring-specificity-ON"

\end_inset

c with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:off-SAC-contact"

\end_inset

d).
 Second, the On SAC is contacted strongly by two transient BC types, while
 the Off SAC receives strong contact from a single transient BC type.
 Third, BC contact on distal SAC dendrites is relatively scarcer for the
 On than the Off circuit (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Off-SAC-(red)"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current study comes with several caveats.
 First, while most of the available evidence supports the sustained-transient
 classification of On BC types adopted in this paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Baden:2013uq,Borghuis:2013uq"

\end_inset

, the literature contains at least one divergent report about this classificatio
n 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ichinose:2014aa"

\end_inset

.
 Second, synaptic connectivity cannot be identified with certainty in e2198,
 because of an unconventional staining technique that left intracellular
 organelles invisible.
 Therefore we rely on contact between cells as an indirect indicator of
 connectivity.
 Third, motion computation by SAC dendrites might involve biophysics of
 SAC dendrites 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gavrikov:2003om,tukker2004direction,Hausselt:2007nx"

\end_inset

, which is not incompatible with our hypothetical mechanism involving space-time
 wiring specificity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We were able to divide BC5 into three types (BC5t, BC5o, and BC5i), based
 on differences in stratification.
 Using patterns of contact with two ganglion cell types, we also replicated
 the prior two-way division by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

 of BC5 into BC5A and BC5R, and found that BC5A corresponds almost perfectly
 with BC5i.
 We were able to assign all BC5 cells to either BC5A and BC5R, because our
 reconstructions of the ganglion cell types are more complete than those
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

.
 In the future, we expect contact or connectivity to replace stratification
 as the main property used to classify cells into types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "seung2009reading,seung2012connectome,jonas2015automatic"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wassle2009cone"

\end_inset

 defined BC5 using a 5-HT3R-EGFP transgenic mouse line.
 They speculated that the line labeled two BC5 types, because of the high
 density of labeled cells, and because two BC5 types had been molecularly
 distinguished in rat 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fyk2007differential"

\end_inset

.
 However, they were unable to find molecular markers distinguishing BC5
 types in mouse.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Duan:2014rr"

\end_inset

 showed that Kcng4 and Cdh9 Cre lines label the same cells as 5-HT3R-EGFP.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "haverkamp2009expression"

\end_inset

 found that the BC5 cells in the 5-HT3R-EGFP line were all CaBP5-positive.
 BC5t may be CaBP5-negative (Haruhisa Okawa and Rachel Wong, private communicati
on).
 If this is the case, it follows that BC5o and BC5i correspond to the two
 types in the 5-HT3R-EGFP transgenic line.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The catalog of mouse BC types is likely complete.
 Our claim is based on two assumptions: (1) every BC type tiles the retina
 with little overlap, and (2) there are no large BCs, which would be rare
 and therefore could have been missed by our reconstructions and those of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Helmstaedter:2013zr"

\end_inset

.
 One anomaly is that BC1 and BC2 tilings exhibit more overlap than those
 of other types (Extended Data Figure 6 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "Kim:2014sf"

\end_inset

).
 The overlap is not enough to allow defining a third type that fully tiles
 the retina; a hypothetical third type would be sparse in its coverage.
 Another qualification is that our reconstructions come from a single location
 in a retina, so we cannot exclude the possibility that cell types vary
 across the retina.
 
\end_layout

